{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"413f89a0-4cf5-49ec-bf75-d50ec8e34bed","content":"Good news — `dotnet-dump` is already installed. I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current directory though.\n\nTo analyze your dump, here's what to do:\n\n1. **Open the dump** (replace with your file path):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your/file.dmp\n   ```\n\n2. **Key commands** once inside the analyzer:\n   | Command | Purpose |\n   |---|---|\n   | `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n   | `pe` (or `printexception`) | Print last exception details |\n   | `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n   | `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n   | `dso` (or `dumpstackobjects`) | Objects on the stack |\n   | `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary |\n   | `exit` | Quit the analyzer |\n\n3. **Typical crash investigation flow:**\n   - Run `pe` to see if there's an unhandled exception\n   - Run `clrthreads` to find threads with exceptions\n   - Use `setthread` + `clrstack` to inspect each thread\n   - Use `dso` to examine objects on the faulting thread\n\nIf you can share the dump file path (or copy it here), I can run these commands interactively for you.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17102376-baf5-4ee6-8dae-01145cc8cb5f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has `dotnet-dump` installed, but there's no .dmp file in the current directory. I should ask where their dump file is located, and give them guidance on how to analyze it.","outputTokens":391,"requestId":"7842:926CA:1E4EDAE:21E3DA9:69FA9F50"},"id":"6dcbc064-28a9-4713-8a73-25379dde8cc7","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:55:15.431Z","parentId":"2d317502-66e4-4b73-b1a0-c0a0064c69b8"}
